=========================================
C++ MAP (RED-BLACK TREE) - STL NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::map?
---------------------
std::map is an associative container that stores elements as:
(key, value) pairs in sorted order of keys.

Example:
map<int, string> m;

m[1] = "one";
m[2] = "two";

Result:
1 -> "one"
2 -> "two"

-----------------------------------------
2. Internal Implementation
-----------------------------------------
std::map is implemented using:

👉 RED-BLACK TREE (Self-balancing BST)

Properties:
- Balanced Binary Search Tree
- Height = O(log n)
- Keeps keys sorted automatically

Node structure (conceptually):
+-------+--------+--------+--------+
| key   | value  | left   | right  |
+-------+--------+--------+--------+

-----------------------------------------
3. Why Red-Black Tree?
-----------------------------------------
Because it guarantees:

✔ O(log n) insert
✔ O(log n) delete
✔ O(log n) search

Even in worst case, tree remains balanced.

-----------------------------------------
4. Key Properties of std::map
-----------------------------------------
- Stores unique keys only
- Keys are always sorted (ascending by default)
- No duplicate keys allowed
- Custom comparator allowed

-----------------------------------------
5. Time Complexities
-----------------------------------------
Operation        Complexity
--------------------------------
insert           O(log n)
erase            O(log n)
find             O(log n)
access []        O(log n)
lower_bound      O(log n)
upper_bound      O(log n)

-----------------------------------------
6. Ordered Nature
-----------------------------------------
map keeps keys sorted automatically.

Example:
m[3] = "C";
m[1] = "A";
m[2] = "B";

Output order:
1 -> A
2 -> B
3 -> C

