8. insert() vs operator[]
-----------------------------------------

insert():
- Does NOT overwrite existing key
- Returns pair<iterator, bool>

m.insert({1, "A"});

operator[]:
- Inserts if key not present
- Overwrites if key exists

m[1] = "A";

-----------------------------------------
9. find() Function
-----------------------------------------
Returns iterator to key if found
Else returns end()

if(m.find(10) != m.end())
    cout << "Found";

-----------------------------------------
10. lower_bound / upper_bound
-----------------------------------------

lower_bound(x):
- First element >= x

upper_bound(x):
- First element > x

Example:
keys = 1, 3, 5, 7

lower_bound(4) -> 5
upper_bound(5) -> 7

-----------------------------------------
11. Iterator Invalidation
-----------------------------------------
VERY IMPORTANT:

✔ insert() → does NOT invalidate iterators
✔ erase() → invalidates only erased element
✔ other iterators remain valid

Reason:
Red-black tree does not shift elements.

-----------------------------------------
12. Why map is slower than unordered_map?
-----------------------------------------
Because:
- map = O(log n) (tree traversal)
- unordered_map = O(1) average (hash table)

-----------------------------------------
13. When to use map?
-----------------------------------------
Use map when:
✔ Need sorted keys
✔ Need range queries (lower_bound, upper_bound)
✔ Need ordered traversal

Avoid when:
✗ Only need fast access (use unordered_map)

-----------------------------------------
14. Real-world Use Cases
-----------------------------------------
- Dictionary / word frequency (sorted)
- Range queries
- Scheduling with priority keys
- Ordered indexing systems
- Competitive programming problems

-----------------------------------------
15. ONE-LINE INTERVIEW ANSWER
-----------------------------------------
std::map is an ordered associative container implemented as a Red-Black Tree that stores key-value pairs in sorted order and supports O(log n) insert, delete, and search operations while maintaining balanced tree structure.
